Question: The error message came up "The format of this title (WMA Audiobook) is not compatible with the picture"
Answer: This error can be resolved by removing the titles from your computer, clearing the temporary internet files, and downloading the files again.    ** Please note that you must install OverDrive Media Console v3.2 to transfer select WMA Audiobooks to your iPod.     Once OMC v3.2 is installed (or confirmed that you are using the latest version), please work through the following:    Remove the title from the OverDrive Media Console:  1. Open the OverDrive Media Console and delete the problem title(s).  2. Verify that the title has been removed from the following folder: C:Documents and Settings{username}My DocumentsMy Media{format of book}{name of book}    Clear the Temporary Internet Files:   Internet Explorer 6:  1. In Internet Explorer, go to Tools > Internet Options.  2. On the 'General' tab, in the 'Temporary Internet Files' section, click the 'Delete Files' button.  3. Check the 'Delete all offline content' checkbox.  4. Once completed, please also click the ‘Delete Cookies’ button.  5. Click 'OK'.    Internet Explorer 7:  1. In Internet Explorer, go to Tools > Internet Options.  2. On the 'General' tab, in the Browsing history' section, click the 'Delete' button.  3. Click the 'Delete all’ button at the bottom of this menu.  4. Click 'Yes'.    Internet Explorer 8:  1. In Internet Explorer, go to Tools > Internet Options.  2. On the 'General' tab, in the 'Browsing history' section, click the 'Delete' button.  3. In the Delete Browsing History dialog box, clear all of the check boxes except for 'Temporary Internet Files'.  4. Click 'Delete'.    Return to the OverDrive Downloadable Media Collection to download the title again. Once the title is downloaded,  transfer the title to your iPod using the OverDrive Media Console:    1. Connect a portable player to your computer.  2. In OverDrive Media Console, highlight the title you wish to transfer and click the 'Transfer' button. The OverDrive Media Console Transfer Wizard is displayed.  3. Verify that the correct title is displayed on the first screen of the Transfer Wizard and click 'Next'. The Transfer Wizard searches for a connected portable device.   4. In the 'Confirm' dialog box, select the Part(s) you want to transfer by checking the box(es) next to the Part name(s).    5. Click 'Next' to begin transferring the file(s) to the device. When the file transfer is complete, the Transfer Wizard displays a 'success' message.  6. Click 'Finish' to exit the Transfer Wizard. Disconnect the portable device.    For additional information go to http://help.overdrive.com/ or http://answers.ccclib.org/a.php?qid=749

I  have two Nooks, a Nook Color and a smaller Nook Simple Touch. Until recently I have been able to add an e- book to both Nooks after I have downloaded the e-book to the Adobe Digital Editions. For the last few days I have only been able to drag the book to my Nook Color but when I try to drag the book into my Nook Simple Touch I get a message that says " files unable to be copied" and " no permission to copy document here." I would really like to have  the e-books on both of my Nooks because I use them in different places. My Nook Color at home and the other one when I am in town.
Answer: The following answer was taken from http://forums.adobe.com/message/4001968?tstart=0#4001968 or try http://help.overdrive.com/article/0476/Getting-started-with-a-NOOK  Most of the time someone runs into this situation, the publisher or distributor has assigned digital rights that do not permit copying the ebook from the original download to another device.  The message you're getting is probably coming from the digital rights that have been assigned by the publisher or the distributor to that particular ebook.  You can check this by looking at the Item Info for the particular ebook that won't transfer.  Here's how you do that:         Go to Library view in ADE.    Then, put your cursor on the small triangle that appears next to the name of the ebook.    A drop-down menu will appear with the choice 'Item Info'.    Click on that bar, and you'll see information about the ebook displayed.    In the middle are the digital rights that have been assigned.    The ebook in question may have a 'Copying: not allowed' setting.  If it does, then there's nothing that you can do via ADE

Question: I am working on a proposal that involves implementing different apps in teaching business courses more specifically, international business and strategy. One aspect I need to incorporate is a measurement tool to evaluate the effectiveness of the particular apps used in the classroom. Are you aware of any questionnaires, surveys or measurements that I can use as a reference?   Ideally, I would like to incorporate a pre-post type of analysis to help  understand the effectiveness of the app/technology in the classroom.
Answer: This is an interesting question and I found a couple of articles that might help. Most of the research seems to have been done internationally, and the terms they're using are "mobile computing" or "mobile learning."    The first is from Macedonia (!). It's called Assessing Effectiveness in Mobile Learning by Devising MLUAT (Mobile Learning Usability Attribute Testing) Methodology  by Bekim Fetaji, Mirlinda Ebibi, Majlinda Fetaji (INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF COMPUTERS AND COMMUNICATIONS Issue 3, Volume 5, 2011). "Mobile learning" by their definition is any handheld computer, such as an iPhone or tablet. Their approach is to assess both the user experience and the effectiveness of the application.    The second is: Enrico Bertini, Silvia Gabrielli, and Stephen Kimani. 2006. Appropriating and assessing heuristics for mobile computing. In Proceedings of the working conference on Advanced visual interfaces (AVI '06). ACM, New York, NY, USA, 119-126. DOI=10.1145/1133265.1133291 http://doi.acm.org/10.1145/1133265.1133291 (If you have problems with this link, you can find the article in the library's ACM Digital Library database.)    On the lighter side, here are some checklists and rubrics used in the K-12 environment that could be adapted. Let me know if any of the above are what you're looking for. If not, I can give it another try.

I was wondering if you can help me find the essay by Bridget Riley titled The Pleasures of Sight? I looked in JSTOR and Art full text and was unable to find it. I'm having a show on the 29th and would like to read it. Thank you for your help, please feel free to contact me with any questions.
Answer: I have two recommendations:    1.  Request this book on Link+:    The eye's mind : Bridget Riley, collected writings 1965-2009 / edited by Robert Kudielka.  Imprint London : Ridinghouse in association with Thames & Hudson ; Santa Monica, CA : Distributed by RAM, 2009.  Edition Rev. and extended 2nd ed.  http://csul.iii.com/record=b30533504~S0    I also found reference to the item in the bibliography of this website:    http://collection.britishcouncil.org/collection/artist/5/18687/object/44956    1. Riley in interview with Michael Craig-Martin, in Bridget Riley: Selected Paintings 1961–1999, exh. cat. (Düsseldorf: Hatje Cantz, 2000), 68.  2. Riley in dialogue with Michael Craig-Martin, in Robert Kudielka (ed.), Bridget Riley: Dialogues on Art (London: Zwemmer, 1995), 56.  3. Riley in conversation with Robert Kudielka (1972), in Paul Moorhouse (ed.), Bridget Riley, exh. cat. (London: Tate, 2003), 209.  4. Bridget Riley, ‘The Pleasures of Sight’ (1984), in Moorhouse (ed.), 213–14.    The Moorhouse item is:   Bridget Riley / general editor, Paul Moorhouse ; contributions by Robert Kudielka and Richard Shiff. London : Tate, 2003.  The essay you want should be on pages 213-214.    The library has a copy, but it is checked out.  Hopefully you are the one that has it, but if not, you can get it from Link+ as well: http://csul.iii.com/record=b17481013~S0    How's that? Question: Is it possible to read an ADOBE Digital 2.0 book on a Kindle?     I have downloaded an Adobe pdf format book to my labptop, a Windows XP, Sony VAIO.  Is it possible to read the Adobe pdf file on ny new Kindle?  My Kindle is  a Kindle Fire HD?
Answer: According to the following http://forums.adobe.com/thread/945620   Amazon has decided to 'capture' the Kindle and uses proprietary software and digital ebook encoding to keep it linked to Amazon's site only.  AFAIK, Adobe products won't work with or on the Kindle.  I'm not sure that the Kindle supports any Adobe digital formats either.  You may have been toldthat Adobe Digital Editions was 'required' to transfer ebooks to the Kindle because the person or persons who told you that didn't realize that.    There are some independent sources for ebooks in Kindle format, however. If you use them, then you can download the material to your computer directly - not through ADE - and then transfer it to the Kindle using your computer utilities.  One of these sources is gutenberg.org - but theirebooks are generally older.        If you go to our website at http://www.sjpl.org/downloads there are various options for free software to view e-books and other e-materials. You will need to download the software first to your computer before you will be able to access  the materials and you will also need a valid library card and and pin number. It is also important to note that Kindles are limited to OverDrive and Axis 360 with Kindle Fire. There is also a Need Help section on this page with frequently asked questions and tips.

I'm looking for some direction on a new project for my MARA 210 course. The goal is to find and explore a current academic research effort regarding the management of electronic records. I've already gone into the Libguides to Library & Information Science, and after a bit of poking around found a note that suggested looking in the Emerald database. I did that and searched on "management of electronic records", and "academic research" AND "management of electronic records" ... where I eventually stumbled upon the following research paper (which sounds promising):    Preserving records in the cloud  Type: Research paper  Author(s): Jan Askhoj, Shigeo Sugimoto, Mitsuharu Nagamori  Source: Records Management Journal Volume: 21 Issue: 3 2011    My search results:   http://www.emeraldinsight.com.libaccess.sjlibrary.org/search.htm?ct=all&st1="management+of+electronic+records"&fd1=all&mm1=all&bl2=and&st2=&fd2=all&mm2=all&bl3=and&st3=&fd3=all&mm3=all&ys=2010&ye=2013&ec=0&ec=1&bf=0&bf=1&search=Search&cd=ac    The problem is that my approach is a bit haphazard and I would appreciate some insight on how I might better approach this sort of task, where i'm more in control, instead of sort of wandering like a beachcomber and finding things that way. In particular, how could I better approach finding current academic research efforts in records management?
Answer: Hi, John! As you've discovered, research in this area is delightfully (read: "annoyingly") dispersed and shows up in a lot of different databases. I've found that Google Scholar is the best place to start when researching for MARA. First, if you haven't already, you want to set up Google Scholar to search across the SJSU databases. Now when you do a search, you'll be looking across all 300+ databases at one time.    Try a search like this one:    ("records management" OR "cloud computing") (universities OR "higher education")    In Google, uppercase "OR" works just like in a database. (This is just about the only time that case matters in Google.) Putting the phrases in quotes means Google will search on them as a concept rather than as two separate words.    I wasn't sure if you were looking for how universities are using electronic records management or just academic articles on that subject. If it's the latter, you can drop the phrases in the second set of parentheses. As its name suggests, Google Scholar by its nature searches only across the academic literature.    Once you find an article you like and are in the database, look for a link in the article record that says "Related items" or "Similar articles." This is a quick way to find other articles on the topic you're interested in.    Another approach is to limit your search to particular journals prominent in the records management field.

I would recommend that you take a look at these books and resources:    https://catalog.sjlibrary.org/record=b3867791~S1  https://catalog.sjlibrary.org/record=b3009813~S1  http://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=info:L7q3-TLLtgwJ:scholar.google.com/&output=instlink&hl=en&as_sdt=0,5&scillfp=491939973356752281&oi=lle    Your questions are quite broad. The title is held for 3 days (72 hours) from the time an email notification is sent to the customer. If not checked out within that time it will be automatically returned to the collection and must be requested again.    3. Once a the hold item is added to the bookbag it must be checked out within 30 minutes or it will be automatically returned to the collection and must be requested again.

Answer: Yes, you can return OverDrive eBooks early by using Adobe Digital Editions. If you're using an  OverDrive app on a device, you can return early using the app.     Step 1   Bring up Adobe Digital Editions,    Step 2   Make sure you are in the Library View ( the row of books icon below the Adobe Digital Editions icon)    Step 3 Mouse over the book cover you want to return    Step 4 There is an arrow to the left called “Item Options”, click on it    Step 5 The 4th item down is “Return borrowed item", click on it    Step 6  A message will pop up and ask "Are you sure you want to return borrowed item"    Step 7  Click return and the item is returned to the library.

Answer: Here are the instructions for returning a Kindle book:    1. An eBook checked out on the Kindle is returned through Amazon. Got to www.amazon.com and from the Kindle menu on the right select “Manage Your Kindle”.    2. Sign into your Amazon account.    3. Select the “Actions” drop down menu next to the took you want to return; the words public library will appear next to any library eBooks.    4. From the menu select “Return this book” make sure to avoid selecting “Delete from library” as this will delete the book from your Kindle Library but WILL NOT RETURN IT.    5. To remove it from the list, select Actions again, and from the dropdown menu select “Delete from library”

Question: I did not use my sjsu library log in for quite a while.  Can you remind me of the procedures. Please remind me of how to use the database. what is my pin#?  I wanted to find this article and I put this link in the search section but the search engine was searching and searching and did not give me the full text.  Please help me.  Integrating a Transcultural Perspective into the Social Work Curriculum: A Descriptive and Exploratory Study (EJ964164)   Share       Author(s):   Sen, Soma;  Can you also please also  let me know if going to google scholar is the same as going into sjsu library website , right?
Answer: I am not able to help you with your pin number. If you have not changed it, it will not have changed. If your account has been inactive for a while, however, you may need to see circulation services to reactivate the account. You can either go to the circulation desk on the 1st floor of the library or contact them with the information below:  Phone: 1-408-808-2000   Email: circ.sjpl@sjlibrary.org    Google Scholar is not the same as the library website. Google scholar searches a variety of sources which may or may not be available in the library. The link below provides a video that lets you know how you can connect google scholar to the library resources if you prefer to search there.  http://library.sjsu.edu/video/customizing-google-scholar    If you do not search in google scholar, below is my instructions for finding an article at the library when you have the full citation information in the future. The journal for the article given has an embargo period, so it is not available in the library for 18 months after publication, so you will need to request it via interlibrary loan to access it. Here are links to two videos about using interlibrary loan and the webpage you can create an account from if you haven't already.  http://library.sjsu.edu/video/interlibrary-services-illiad-creating-account  http://library.sjsu.edu/video/interlibrary-services-illiad-placing-request  http://library.sjsu.edu/interlibrary-services/interlibrary-services-formerly-interlibrary-loan      1) Click on ejournals tab in search bar on the library homepage  2) Search by journal title to see if we have your issue available electronically, if  we do double check that the year range matches the year of your citation. Open the link that matches and navigate to your year/volume to find the article.  3) Check the library catalog for print versions if we don't have it electronically.  Look for the journal title without [electronic access] to locate what we have available in print on the lower level of the library. Check the line that says "library has..." to make sure we have your year. Print journals can't be taken out of the library, so bring a usb drive to scan the article or change to make copies at 20 cents a page.  4) Request via interlibrary loan if we don't have it electronically or in print.
